In the next two problems you will perform block matching motion estimation between two consecutive video frames. Follow the instructions below to complete this problem.

(1) Download the two video frames from frame_1 and frame_2. The frames/images are of height 288 and width 352.

(2) Load the frame with file name "frame_1.jpg" into a [Math Processing Error] MATLAB array using function "imread", and then convert the array type from 8-bit integer to real number using function "double" or "cast" (note that the range of intensity values after conversion is between 0 and 255). Denote by [Math Processing Error] the converted MATLAB array. Repeat this step for the frame with file name "frame_2.jpg" and denote the resulting MATLAB array by [Math Processing Error]. In this problem, [Math Processing Error] corresponds to the current frame, and [Math Processing Error] corresponds to the previous frame (i.e., the reference frame).

(3) Consider the [Math Processing Error] target block in [Math Processing Error] that has its upper-left corner at [Math Processing Error] and lower-right corner at [Math Processing Error]. Note this is MATLAB coordinate convention, i.e., the first number between the parenthesis is the row index extending from [Math Processing Error] to [Math Processing Error] and the second number is the column index extending from [Math Processing Error] to [Math Processing Error]. This target block is therefore a [Math Processing Error] sub-array of [Math Processing Error].

(4) Denote the target block by [Math Processing Error]. Motion estimation via block matching searches for the [Math Processing Error] sub-array of [Math Processing Error] that is "most similar" to [Math Processing Error]. Recall in the video lectures we have introduced various forms of matching criteria, e.g., correlation coefficient, mean-squared-error (MSE), mean-absolute-error (MAE), etc.

In this problem, we use MAE as the matching criterion. Given two blocks [Math Processing Error] and [Math Processing Error] both of size [Math Processing Error], the MAE is defined as [Math Processing Error]. To find the block in [Math Processing Error] that is most similar to [Math Processing Error] in the MAE sense, you will need to scan through all the [Math Processing Error] blocks in [Math Processing Error], compute the MAE between each of these blocks and [Math Processing Error], and find the one that yields the smallest value of MAE.

Note in practice motion search is only performed over a certain region of the reference frame, but for the sake of simplicity, we perform motion search over the entire reference frame [Math Processing Error] in this problem and the next. When you find the matched block in [Math Processing Error], enter the sum of the x and y coordinates of the upper-left corner of the matched block in MATLAB convention. For example, if the matched block has the upper-left corner located at [Math Processing Error] then you must enter 30.
